headline.main: NEW-YORK CITY.; The Cape de Verde Sufferers--Sympathy in the Seventeenth Ward. Public Health. Mowing In the Park. Bully Brooks Challenged by a Gentleman of His Own Kidney. District Superintendent of Schools. Buckleys' New Hall. Accident to Judge Slaughter. Hogs and Oxen in the Streets on Sunday. Central Park Police. The North American New-York State Convention. Paving Duane Street. Falling Bricks. The Worm Nuisance. Fatal Powder Explosion. Found Drowned. Fires.

docs.lead_paragraph: A meeting of residents of the Seventeenth Ward was held on Wednesday night at the Sixth-street Presbyterian Church, near Second-avenue, for the purpose of sympathizing with the Cape de Verdi sufferers and of collecting funds for their relief. The meeing was not large, consisting of only thirty three persons, but was quite enthusiastic.

docs.lead_paragraph: On Friday last the pupils of the various departments of Twentieth Ward School No. 33, in Thirty-fifth-street, neat Ninth-avenue, gave a reception. The exercises commenced in the Primary Department, where were assembled 717 girls and boys, under the direction of Miss CLARA, M. EDMONDS, Principal, with nine assistant teachers.
